<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1441,2006]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1513,1537]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name refers to the similarity of the new species to the Peruvian 
<taxonomicName authority="McLachlan 1871" authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1871" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saucia">
<emphasis box="[1200,1301,1514,1537]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">S. saucia</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="McLachlan, R." pageId="9" pageNumber="32" pagination="98 - 141" refId="ref7976" refString="McLachlan, R. (1871) On new forms, etc., of extra-European Trichopterous insects. Journal of the Linnean Society of London, Zoology, 11, 98 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1870. tb 02011. x" type="journal article" year="1871">McLachlan 1871</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1441,2006]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1585,1610]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[423,526,1585,1610]" captionStart="FIGURES 15" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1539,1561]" captionTargetBox="[185,1404,198,1508]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[175,1411,193,1517]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 15A–15F. Trichoptera spp., photos of adults, dorsal view. 15A, Atopsyche viejae spec. nov., male paratype; 15B, Atopsyche flavoantennata spec. nov., female paratype; 15C, Smicridea colombosaucia spec. nov., male paratype; 15D, Polycentropus joergenseni Ulmer 1909, male; 15E, Phylloicus monserratensis spec. nov., male paratype; 15F, Marilia bogotaensis spec. nov., male paratype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606160/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Fig. 15C</figureCitation>
): Length of each forewing 
<quantity box="[825,892,1585,1610]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
, wingspan 
<quantity box="[1016,1119,1585,1610]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="13.5">13.5 mm</quantity>
. Head dark brown; antennae and palpi brown; legs light brown; forewings fuscous, each with indistinct gold-brown fascia in apical third, hindwings with long curved R2+3. Anterolateral process of sternum V as long as sternum; with two pairs of internal sacs with reticulated membrane.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1441,2006]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[381,454,1729,1754]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1921,1943]" captionTargetBox="[198,1411,225,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[174,1411,193,1901]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Trichoptera spp., male genitalia. 7A–7C, Polycentropus joergenseni Ulmer 1909, scale = 0.5 mm: 7A, left lateral; 7B, ventral; 7C, dorsal.. 8A–8C, Xiphocentron laviejae spec. nov., scale = 0.3 mm: 8A, left lateral, with phallic apparatus in situ; 8B, ventral; 8C dorsal. 9A–9D, Smicridea colombosaucia spec. nov., scale = 0.25 mm: 9A,left lateral, with phallic apparatus in situ; 9B, phallic apparatus, left lateral with everted endotheca; 9C, dorsal; 9D, ventral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606154/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">Figs 9</figureCitation>
A–9D): Segment IX in lateral view with anterior margin convex, dorsal side broadly rounded and with granulate surface, in dorsal view longitudinal keel broadly triangular with rounded posterior margin. Tergum X in dorsal view membranous dorsomedially, lateral processes rounded distally and divided by strong ridge; in lateral view ventrolateral margin strongly sclerotized. Inferior appendages each two-segmented, in lateral view each with basal segment longer than apical segment, tubular and thick, in ventral view tubular and curved mesad, apical segment sickle-shaped. Phallic apparatus long and tubular, in lateral view broad and strongly curved basally, dorsal endothecal lobes subtriangular, with sclerotized tips, ventral endothecal lobes subquadrate, with sclerotized distal margins and apicoventral lobe projecting ventrad in everted state.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,151,176]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Mey &amp; Ospina-Torres, 2018" authorityName="Mey &amp; Ospina-Torres" authorityYear="2018" box="[333,630,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombosaucia" status="spec. nov.">
<emphasis box="[333,630,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Smicridea colombosaucia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[641,761,152,176]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[641,761,152,176]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" rank="species">spec. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1871" box="[954,1105,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatella">
<emphasis box="[954,968,152,175]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[988,1105,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">fasciatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group within the subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[151,265,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,265,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Smicridea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The new species seems to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1871" box="[818,920,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saucia">
<emphasis box="[818,832,188,211]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[847,920,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">saucia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Flint 1974 b" authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1974" box="[977,1281,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviuncata">
<emphasis box="[977,991,188,211]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1006,1139,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">breviuncata</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Flint, O. S. Jr." box="[1147,1281,188,213]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" pagination="1 - 65" refId="ref7391" refString="Flint, O. S. Jr. (1974 b) Studies of Neotropical caddisflies, XVII: The genus Smicridea from North and Central America (Trichoptera: Hydropsychidae). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 167, 1 - 65. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.167" type="journal article" year="1974">Flint 1974b</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, based on the architecture of tergum X with the rounded distal margin and the subtriangular, dorsal processes of the endotheca. The dividing ridge of tergum X, the broad dorsal process of segment IX, and the sickle-shaped harpago separate the new species from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1871" box="[354,455,296,319]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saucia">
<emphasis box="[354,455,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">S. saucia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and related species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">
Male specimens collected in alcohol usually have the processes of the endotheca inverted within the phallic tube. The phallic apparatus is often depicted in this position. But with these structures fully everted, the apex of the phallic apparatus appears to be rather different in shape. In the 
<figureCitation box="[864,934,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1921,1943]" captionTargetBox="[198,1411,225,1864]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[174,1411,193,1901]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Trichoptera spp., male genitalia. 7A–7C, Polycentropus joergenseni Ulmer 1909, scale = 0.5 mm: 7A, left lateral; 7B, ventral; 7C, dorsal.. 8A–8C, Xiphocentron laviejae spec. nov., scale = 0.3 mm: 8A, left lateral, with phallic apparatus in situ; 8B, ventral; 8C dorsal. 9A–9D, Smicridea colombosaucia spec. nov., scale = 0.25 mm: 9A,left lateral, with phallic apparatus in situ; 9B, phallic apparatus, left lateral with everted endotheca; 9C, dorsal; 9D, ventral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2606154/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">Figs 9</figureCitation>
A–9B, the inverted and everted stages of the phallic apparatus are depicted to demonstrate these differences. 
<bibRefCitation author="Flint, O. S. Jr. &amp; Reyes, L." box="[896,1263,439,464]" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" pagination="474 - 492" refId="ref7553" refString="Flint, O. S. Jr. &amp; Reyes, L. (1991) Studies of Neotropical Caddisflies, XLVI: The Trichoptera of the Rio Moche basin, Department of La Libertad, Peru. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 104 (3), 474 - 492." type="journal article" year="1991">Flint &amp; Reyes (1991: 481–482)</bibRefCitation>
reported some variation in the tip of the phallic apparatus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1871" box="[663,764,476,500]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saucia">
<emphasis box="[663,764,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="33">S. saucia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this was probably due to a partially everted endotheca.
</paragraph>
